<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 9:7<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I288e2b10630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>9.</label.designator><headtext>Hearsay</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id7203e3d682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>9:7.</label.designator><headtext>Admissions—Personal knowledge not necessary</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>An admission need not be founded on personal knowledge of the declarant.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic4fe74007fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>] Federal and state practice treat this issue the same. <eos/><bos/>In federal practice, an admission is not excludable merely because the speaker lacks personal knowledge.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic4fe9b107fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>] Federal practice permits an out-of-court confession of “fault” or “liability” to be admitted against its maker.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic4fe9b117fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3<page no="289"/></footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Generally, admissions of fault or liability are received in evidence without regard to the personal knowledge of the declarant[<footnote.reference refid="Ic4fe9b127fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>] even when the statement is a legal conclusion of negligence or fault.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic4fe9b137fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Statements relating to a question of law are not admissible.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic4fe9b147fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">6</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>A party&apos;s statement as to rights which could be exercised under an assignment contract has been held not to be an admission.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic4fe9b157fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">7</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017166" w-serial-number="1990063802" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3cd0b2a27fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Howell Mill/Collier v. Pennypacker&apos;s</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic4fe9b167fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">8</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Court of Appeals held that a party&apos;s conclusion regarding when rental payments were to commence under a lease agreement was not an admission since this was a legal conclusion regarding the construction of the lease agreement.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic4fe74007fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017166" w-serial-number="1860002755" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000359" ID="I3ccd57417fc011ea988285db8533e975">Kitchen v. Robbins, 29 Ga. 713, 1860 WL 2307 (1860)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017166" w-serial-number="1923104518" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I3ccd57457fc011ea988285db8533e975">Chero Cola Bottling Co. v. Southern Express Co., 29 Ga. App. 656, 116 S.E. 325 (1923)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017166" w-serial-number="0280312688" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="TS" w-pub-number="0134642" ID="I3ccd57467fc011ea988285db8533e975">McCormick on Evidence § 263 (6th ed.)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic4fe9b107fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Mueller and Kirkpatrick, Federal Evidence § 8:44 (3d ed.).<eos/><page no="289"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic4fe9b117fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3<page no="289"/></label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Mueller and Kirkpatrick, Federal Evidence § 8:44 (3d ed.).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic4fe9b127fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017166" w-serial-number="1948104305" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3cceb6d27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Wade v. Drinkard, 76 Ga. App. 159, 45 S.E.2d 231 (1947)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic4fe9b137fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017166" w-serial-number="1901011091" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I3ccf04f27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Central of Georgia Ry. Co. v. Mosely, 112 Ga. 914, 38 S.E. 350 (1901)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic4fe9b147fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017166" w-serial-number="1926104806" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I3ccf7a227fc011ea988285db8533e975">Atlanta &amp; Lowry Nat. Bank v. Maughon, 35 Ga. App. 25, 131 S.E. 916 (1926)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic4fe9b157fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017166" w-serial-number="1990066193" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ccfef527fc011ea988285db8533e975">Southern Business Machines of Savannah, Inc. v. Norwest Financial Leasing, Inc., 194 Ga. App. 253, 390 S.E.2d 402 (1990)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic4fe9b167fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017166" w-serial-number="1990063802" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3cd0d9b27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Howell Mill/Collier Associates v. Pennypacker&apos;s, Inc., 194 Ga. App. 169, 390 S.E.2d 257 (1990)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 9:7<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
